<div id="review_2720505606" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2720505606" />
    <a title="Dmitri" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/73216705-dmitri"><img alt="Dmitri" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1560026165p2/73216705.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2720505606?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dmitri" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dmitri" href="/user/show/73216705-dmitri">Dmitri</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/73216705-dmitri?shelf=china">china</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2720505606" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4328202963537058259">This is the story of a lady who was upper class bred; she didn&apos;t have a problem trying to keep her family fed. At least until she wound up on the wrong end of the Cultural Revolution that is. To be rich was definitely not glorious then. You could end up in prison, which is in fact what happened.<br/><br/>Cheng was a decent person, well-educated in Britain and a Christian by faith. This, and her successful employment by Shell Petroleum, all but guaranteed a visit from the Red Guard. The only question is wh</span>
  <span id="freeText4328202963537058259" style="display:none">This is the story of a lady who was upper class bred; she didn't have a problem trying to keep her family fed. At least until she wound up on the wrong end of the Cultural Revolution that is. To be rich was definitely not glorious then. You could end up in prison, which is in fact what happened.<br /><br />Cheng was a decent person, well-educated in Britain and a Christian by faith. This, and her successful employment by Shell Petroleum, all but guaranteed a visit from the Red Guard. The only question is why it took them so long to come. Once they knocked on her door things spiraled quickly downward.<br /><br />She may have been lulled by a life of ease, but by 1962 a less tolerant breeze was blowing in old Shanghai. Rather than grovel before the green-garbed god of Maoism, she spoke truth to power and consequently paid the price. During imprisonment, her home was confiscated and her daughter beaten to death.<br /><br />Nien Cheng is no literary luminary, nor would she expected to be. This is the personal memoir of a private business person. At times the book has the stilted cadence of a daytime television drama: "When I said this, then they said that". This detracts from her delivery but not from her message.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4328202963537058259" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


